1
00:00:00,110 --> 00:00:05,420
In this video, we are going to learn gRPC for high performance remote procedure calls.

2
00:00:06,050 --> 00:00:11,450
gRPC is an open source remote procedure call system initially developed at Google.

3
00:00:11,930 --> 00:00:17,540
gRPC is a framework to efficiently connect services and build distributed systems.

4
00:00:17,960 --> 00:00:24,980
It is focused on high performance and uses the Http two protocol to transport binary messages.

5
00:00:26,060 --> 00:00:30,500
It relies on the protocol buffer language to define service contracts.

6
00:00:31,280 --> 00:00:38,390
Protocol buffers, also known as protobuf, allows you to define the interface to be used in service

7
00:00:38,390 --> 00:00:41,900
to service communication regardless of the programming language.

8
00:00:42,410 --> 00:00:46,610
It generates cross-platform client and server bindings for many languages.

9
00:00:46,970 --> 00:00:53,450
Most common usage scenarios include connecting services in microservices style architecture and connect

10
00:00:53,450 --> 00:00:57,110
mobile devices browser clients to backend services.

11
00:00:58,430 --> 00:01:04,760
So the gRPC framework allows developers to create services that can communicate with each other efficiently

12
00:01:04,760 --> 00:01:08,480
and independently from their preferred programming language.

13
00:01:09,140 --> 00:01:15,710
Once you define a contract with protobuf, this contract can be used by each service to automatically

14
00:01:15,710 --> 00:01:19,880
generate the code that can sets up the communication infrastructure.

15
00:01:20,480 --> 00:01:26,300
This feature simplifies the creation of the service interactions and together with high performance,

16
00:01:26,300 --> 00:01:33,050
makes gRPC the ideal framework for creating microservices and communicating between inter service communications.

